msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:32
msgid "when accessing an attribute of a {py:class}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "Memory Leaks and Python to JavaScript translations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:37
msgid ""
"Any time a Python to JavaScript translation occurs, it may create a {js:"
"class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy`. To avoid memory leaks, you must store the {js:"
"class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` and {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.destroy` it "
"when you are done with it. Alternatively, you can declare the `PyProxy` with "
"`using`. See {ref}`call-py-from-js` for more info."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:44
msgid "Round trip conversions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:46
msgid ""
"Translating an object from Python to JavaScript and then back to Python is "
"guaranteed to give an object that is equal to the original object. "
"Furthermore, if the object is proxied into JavaScript, then translation back "
"unwraps the proxy, and the result of the round trip conversion `is` the "
"original object (in the sense that they live at the same memory address)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:52
msgid ""
"Translating an object from JavaScript to Python and then back to JavaScript "
"gives an object that is `===` to the original object. Furthermore, if the "
"object is proxied into Python, then translation back unwraps the proxy, and "
"the result of the round trip conversion is the original object (in the sense "
"that they live at the same memory address)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:58
msgid "Implicit conversions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:60
msgid ""
"We implicitly convert immutable types but not mutable types. This ensures "
"that mutable Python objects can be modified from JavaScript and vice-versa. "
"Python has immutable types such as {py:class}`tuple` and {py:class}`bytes` "
"that have no equivalent in JavaScript. In order to ensure that round trip "
"translations yield an object of the same type as the original object, we "
"proxy {py:class}`tuple` and {py:class}`bytes` objects."
msgstr ""

