#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:152
msgid ""
"Note that each of these operations is only supported if the proxied "
"JavaScript object supports the corresponding operation. See {py:class}`the "
"JsProxy API docs <pyodide.ffi.JsProxy>` for the rest of the methods "
"supported on {py:class}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy`. Some other code snippets:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:157
msgid ""
"for v in proxy:\n"
"    # do something\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:162
msgid "is equivalent to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:164
msgid ""
"for (let v of x) {\n"
"  // do something\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:170
msgid ""
"The {py:func}`dir` method has been overloaded to return all keys on the "
"prototype chain of `x`, so `dir(x)` roughly translates to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:173
msgid ""
"function dir(x) {\n"
"  let result = [];\n"
"  do {\n"
"    result.push(...Object.getOwnPropertyNames(x));\n"
"  } while ((x = Object.getPrototypeOf(x)));\n"
"  return result;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:183
msgid ""
"If a JavaScript object has a `[Symbol.dispose]()` method, the `JsProxy` can "
"be used as a context manager:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:186
msgid ""
"from pyodide.code import run_js\n"
"\n"
"f = run_js(\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    function f() {\n"
"        return {\n"
"            disposed: false,\n"
"            [Symbol.dispose]() {\n"
"                this.disposed = true;\n"
"            }\n"
"        };\n"
"    })\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"with f() as x:\n"
"    print(x.disposed) # False\n"
"\n"
"print(x.disposed) # True\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:208
msgid ""
"Likewise, if a JavaScript object has a `[Symbol.asyncDispose]()` method, the "
"`JsProxy` can be used as an async context manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:211
msgid ""
"As a special case, JavaScript {js:class}`Array` and array-like objects such "
"as {js:class}`HTMLCollection`, and {js:class}`NodeList` are container types, "
"but instead of using `array.get(7)` to get the 7th element, JavaScript uses "
"`array[7]`. For these cases, we translate:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`proxy[idx]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`array[idx]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`proxy[idx] = val`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`array[idx] = val`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`idx in proxy`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`idx in array`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`del proxy[idx]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:34
msgid "`array.splice(idx)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:223
msgid ""
"An object is treated as array-like if it is iterable and has a `length` "
"field. An object is treated as an array if ``Array.isArray()`` returns true. "
"Array-like objects that are not arrays or typed arrays are assumed to be "
"immutable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:227
msgid ""
"If you need to access the fields in a JavaScript object, you must use `obj."
"field_name` or if the name of the field is not a valid Python identifier, "
"`getattr(obj, \"field name\")`. If you want to access the fields of the "
"object like `obj[\"field name\"]` you can use {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy."
"as_py_json`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:233
msgid ""
"from pyodide.code import run_js\n"
"\n"
"obj = run_js(\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    ({\n"
"      a: 7,\n"
"      b: 9,\n"
"      $c: 11\n"
"    })\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
")\n"
"obj_map = obj.as_py_json()\n"
"assert obj_map[\"$c\"] == 11\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:249
msgid ""
"Another special case comes from the fact that Python reserved words cannot "
"be used as attributes. For instance, {js:func}`Array.from` and {js:meth}"
"`Promise.finally` cannot be directly accessed because they are Python "
"`SyntaxError`s. Instead we access these attributes with `Array.from_` and "
"`Promise.finally_`. Similarly, to access from Python, `o.from_` you have to "
"use `o.from__` with two underscores (since a single underscore is used for "
"`o.from`). This is reflected in the `dir` of a `JsProxy`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:257
msgid ""
"from pyodide.code import run_js\n"
"o = run_js(\"({finally: 1, return: 2, from: 3, from_: 4})\")\n"
"assert set(dir(o)) == {\"finally_\", \"return_\", \"from_\", \"from__\"}\n"
msgstr ""

