"As a special case, if a PyProxy is created of a dictionary, then "
"`proxy[key]` will fall back to checking for an item in the dictionary if "
"there is no attribute called key. Both PyProxy properties and dictionary "
"attributes take precedence over dictionary keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
msgid "Memory Leaks and PyProxy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:303
msgid ""
"Make sure to destroy PyProxies when you are done with them to avoid memory "
"leaks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:305
msgid ""
"let foo = pyodide.globals.get('foo');\n"
"foo();\n"
"foo.destroy();\n"
"foo(); // throws Error: Object has already been destroyed\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:313
msgid "Explicit Conversion of Proxies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:319
msgid ""
"Explicit conversion of a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` into a native "
"JavaScript object is done with the {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` "
"method. You can also perform such a conversion in Python using {py:func}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.to_js` which behaves in much the same way. By default, the {js:"
"func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` method does a recursive \"deep\" "
"conversion, to do a shallow conversion use `proxy.toJs({depth : 1})`. In "
"addition to [the normal type conversion](type-translations_py2js-table), the "
"{js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` method performs the following explicit "
"conversions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
msgid "{py:class}`list`, {py:class}`tuple`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "{js:class}`Array`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "{py:class}`dict`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
msgid "{js:data}`Object`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
