msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:300
msgid "{js:class}`TypedArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:336
msgid ""
"\\* Examples of buffers include {py:class}`bytes` objects and numpy "
"{external+numpy:ref}`arrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:339
msgid ""
"If you need to convert {py:class}`dict` instead to {js:data}`Object`, you "
"can pass {js:func}`Object.fromEntries` as the `dict_converter` argument: "
"`proxy.toJs({dict_converter : Object.fromEntries})`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:343
msgid ""
"In JavaScript, {js:class}`Set` keys are compared using object identity "
"unless the key is an immutable type (meaning a {js:data}`String`, a {js:data}"
"`Number`, a {js:data}`BigInt`, a {js:data}`Boolean`, {js:data}`undefined`, "
"or {js:data}`null`). {js:data}`Object` keys are all treated as strings. On "
"the other hand, in Python, {py:class}`dict` and {py:class}`set` keys are "
"compared using deep equality. If a key is encountered in a {py:class}`dict` "
"or {py:class}`set` that would have different semantics in JavaScript than in "
"Python, then a {py:exc}`~pyodide.ffi.ConversionError` will be thrown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:352
msgid ""
"See {ref}`buffer_tojs` for the behavior of {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy."
"toJs` on buffers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "Memory Leaks and toJs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:358
msgid ""
"The {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` method can create many proxies at "
"arbitrary depth. It is your responsibility to manually {js:meth}`~pyodide."
"ffi.PyProxy.destroy` these proxies if you wish to avoid memory leaks. The "
"`pyproxies` argument to {js:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` is designed to "
"help with this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:362
msgid ""
"let pyproxies = [];\n"
"proxy.toJs({pyproxies});\n"
"// Do stuff\n"
"// pyproxies contains the list of proxies created by `toJs`. We can destroy "
"them\n"
"// when we are done with them\n"
"for(let px of pyproxies){\n"
"    px.destroy();\n"
"}\n"
"proxy.destroy();\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:373
msgid ""
"As an alternative, if you wish to assert that the object should be fully "
"converted and no proxies should be created, you can use `proxy."
"toJs({create_pyproxies : false})`. If a proxy would be created, a {py:exc}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.ConversionError` is raised instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:383
msgid ""
"Explicit conversion of a {py:class}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy` into a native "
"Python object is done with the {py:meth}`JsProxy.to_py() <pyodide.ffi."
"JsProxy.to_py>` method. By default, the {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy."
"to_py` method does a recursive \"deep\" conversion, to do a shallow "
"conversion use `proxy.to_py(depth=1)`. The {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy."
"to_py` method performs the following explicit conversions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "{py:class}`list`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "{js:data}`Object`\\*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:355
msgid "{js:class}`Map`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:397
msgid ""
"\\* {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy.to_py` will only convert an {js:data}"
"`Object` into a dictionary if its constructor is {js:data}`Object`, "
"otherwise the object will be left alone. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:401
msgid ""
"class Test {};\n"
"window.x = { \"a\" : 7, \"b\" : 2};\n"
"window.y = { \"a\" : 7, \"b\" : 2};\n"
"Object.setPrototypeOf(y, Test.prototype);\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from js import x, y\n"
"    # x is converted to a dictionary\n"
"    assert x.to_py() == { \"a\" : 7, \"b\" : 2}\n"
"    # y is not a \"Plain Old JavaScript Object\", it's an instance of type "
"Test so it's not converted\n"
"    assert y.to_py() == y\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:415
msgid ""
"In JavaScript, {js:class}`Map` and {js:class}`Set` keys are compared using "
"object identity unless the key is an immutable type (meaning a {js:data}"
"`String`, a {js:data}`Number`, a {js:data}`BigInt`, a {js:data}`Boolean`, "
"{js:data}`undefined`, or {js:data}`null`). On the other hand, in Python, {py:"
"class}`dict` and {py:class}`set` keys are compared using deep equality. If a "
"key is encountered in a {js:class}`Map` or {js:class}`Set` that would have "
"different semantics in Python than in JavaScript, then a {py:exc}`~pyodide."
"ffi.ConversionError` will be thrown. Also, in JavaScript, `true !== 1` and "
"`false !== 0`, but in Python, `True == 1` and `False == 0`. This has the "
"result that a JavaScript map can use `true` and `1` as distinct keys but a "
"Python {py:class}`dict` cannot. If the JavaScript map contains both `true` "
"and `1` a {py:exc}`~pyodide.ffi.ConversionError` will be thrown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:428
msgid "Functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:432
msgid "Calling Python objects from JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:434
msgid ""
"If a Python object is callable, the proxy will be callable too. The "
"arguments will be translated from JavaScript to Python as appropriate, and "
"the return value will be translated from JavaScript back to Python. If the "
"return value is a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy`, you must explicitly "
"destroy it or else it will be leaked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:440
msgid "An example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:442
msgid ""
"let test = pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    def test(x):\n"
"        return [n*n for n in x]\n"
"    test\n"
"`);\n"
"let result_py = test([1,2,3,4]);\n"
"// result_py is a PyProxy of a list.\n"
"let result_js = result_py.toJs();\n"
"// result_js is the array [1, 4, 9, 16]\n"
"// clean up result and test pyproxies\n"
"result_py.destroy();\n"
"test.destroy();\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:457
msgid ""
"Alternatively, with recent JavaScript runtimes you can use the `using` "
"keyword:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:458
msgid ""
"{\n"
"    using test = pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"        def test(x):\n"
"            return [n*n for n in x]\n"
"        test\n"
"    `);\n"
"    using result_py = test([1,2,3,4]);\n"
"    // result_py is a PyProxy of a list.\n"
"    let result_js = result_py.toJs();\n"
"    // result_js is the array [1, 4, 9, 16]\n"
"}\n"
"// JavaScript explicit resource management cleans up proxies at end of "
"scope\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:474
msgid ""
"If a function is intended to be used from JavaScript, you can use {py:func}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.to_js` on the return value. This prevents the return value "
"from leaking without requiring the JavaScript code to explicitly destroy it. "
"This is particularly important for callbacks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:479
msgid ""
"let test = pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from pyodide.ffi import to_js\n"
"    def test(x):\n"
"        return to_js([n*n for n in x])\n"
"    test\n"
"`);\n"
"let result = test([1,2,3,4]);\n"
"// result is the array [1, 4, 9, 16], nothing needs to be destroyed.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:490
msgid ""
"If you need to use a key word argument, use {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi."
"PyCallable.callKwargs`. The last argument should be a JavaScript object with "
"the key value arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:494
msgid ""
"let test = pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from pyodide.ffi import to_js\n"
"    def test(x, *, offset):\n"
"        return to_js([n*n + offset for n in x])\n"
"    to_js(test)\n"
"`);\n"
"let result = test.callKwargs([1,2,3,4], { offset : 7});\n"
"// result is the array [8, 12, 16, 23]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:507
msgid "Calling JavaScript functions from Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:509
msgid ""
"What happens when calling a JavaScript function from Python is a bit more "
"complicated than calling a Python function from JavaScript. If there are any "
"keyword arguments, they are combined into a JavaScript object and used as "
"the final argument. Thus, if you call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:514
msgid "f(a=2, b=3)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:518
msgid ""
"then the JavaScript function receives one argument which is a JavaScript "
"object `{a : 2, b : 3}`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:521
msgid ""
"When a JavaScript function is called, if the return value not a {js:class}"
"`Promise`, a {js:class}`Generator`, or an {js:class}`AsyncGenerator`, any "
"arguments that are PyProxies that were created in the process of argument "
"conversion are also destroyed. If the result is a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi."
"PyProxy` it is also destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:527
msgid ""
"As a result of this, if a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` is persisted to "
"be used later, then it must either be copied using {js:meth}`~pyodide.ffi."
"PyProxy.copy` in JavaScript, or it must be created with {py:func}`~pyodide."
"ffi.create_proxy` or {py:func}`~pyodide.ffi.create_once_callable`. If it's "
"only going to be called once use {py:func}`~pyodide.ffi."
"create_once_callable`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:534
msgid ""
"from pyodide.ffi import create_once_callable\n"
"from js import setTimeout\n"
"def my_callback():\n"
"    print(\"hi\")\n"
"setTimeout(create_once_callable(my_callback), 1000)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:542
msgid ""
"If it's going to be called many times use {py:func}`~pyodide.ffi."
"create_proxy`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:544
msgid ""
"from pyodide.ffi import create_proxy\n"
"from js import document\n"
"def my_callback():\n"
"    print(\"hi\")\n"
"proxy = create_proxy(my_callback)\n"
"document.body.addEventListener(\"click\", proxy)\n"
"# ...\n"
"# make sure to hold on to proxy\n"
"document.body.removeEventListener(\"click\", proxy)\n"
"proxy.destroy()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:557
msgid ""
"When a JavaScript function returns a {js:class}`Promise` (for example, if "
"the function is an async function), it is assumed that the {js:class}"
"`Promise` is going to do some work that uses the arguments of the function, "
"so it is not safe to destroy them until the {js:class}`Promise` resolves. In "
"this case, the proxied function returns a Python {py:class}`~asyncio.Future` "
"instead of the original {js:class}`Promise`. When the {js:class}`Promise` "
"resolves, the result is converted to Python and the converted value is used "
"to resolve the {py:class}`~asyncio.Future`. Then if the result is a {js:"
"class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` it is destroyed. Any PyProxies created in "
"converting the arguments are also destroyed at this point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:568
msgid ""
"Similarly, if the return value is a {js:class}`Generator` or {js:class}"
"`AsyncGenerator`, then the arguments (and all values sent to the generator) "
"are kept alive until it is exhausted, or until {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi."
"JsGenerator.close` is called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:573
msgid "Buffers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:575
msgid "Using JavaScript Typed Arrays from Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:577
msgid ""
"JavaScript {js:class}`ArrayBuffer` and {js:class}`TypedArray` objects are "
"proxied into Python. Python can't directly access arrays if they are outside "
"the WASM heap, so it's impossible to directly use these proxied buffers as "
"Python buffers. You can convert such a proxy to a Python {py:class}"
"`memoryview` using the {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsProxy.to_py` api. This makes "
"it easy to correctly convert the array to a Numpy array using {py:func}"
"`numpy.asarray`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:584
msgid ""
"self.jsarray = new Float32Array([1,2,3, 4, 5, 6]);\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from js import jsarray\n"
"    array = jsarray.to_py()\n"
"    import numpy as np\n"
"    numpy_array = np.asarray(array).reshape((2,3))\n"
"    print(numpy_array)\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:595
msgid ""
"After manipulating `numpy_array` you can assign the value back to `jsarray` "
"using {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsBuffer.assign`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:598
msgid ""
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    numpy_array[1,1] = 77\n"
"    jsarray.assign(a)\n"
"`);\n"
"console.log(jsarray); // [1, 2, 3, 4, 77, 6]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:606
msgid ""
"The {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.JsBuffer.assign` and {py:meth}`~pyodide.ffi."
"JsBuffer.assign_to` methods can be used to assign a JavaScript buffer from / "
"to a Python buffer which is appropriately sized and contiguous. The "
"assignment methods will only work if the data types match, the total length "
"of the buffers match, and the Python buffer is contiguous."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:614
msgid "Using Python Buffer objects from JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:616
msgid ""
"Python objects supporting the [Python Buffer protocol](https://docs.python."
"org/3/c-api/buffer.html) are proxied into JavaScript. The data inside the "
"buffer can be accessed via the {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` method "
"or the {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyBuffer.getBuffer` method. The {js:func}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` API copies the buffer into JavaScript, whereas "
"the {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyBuffer.getBuffer` method allows low level "
"access to the WASM memory backing the buffer. The {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi."
"PyBuffer.getBuffer` API is more powerful but requires care to use correctly. "
"For simple use cases the {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` API should be "
"preferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:628
msgid ""
"If the buffer is zero or one-dimensional, then {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi."
"PyProxy.toJs` will in most cases convert it to a single {js:class}"
"`TypedArray`. However, in the case that the format of the buffer is `'s'`, "
"we will convert the buffer to a string and if the format is `'?'` we will "
"convert it to an {js:class}`Array` of booleans."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:634
msgid ""
"If the dimension is greater than one, we will convert it to a nested "
"JavaScript array, with the innermost dimension handled in the same way we "
"would handle a 1d array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:638
msgid ""
"An example of a case where you would not want to use the {js:func}`~pyodide."
"ffi.PyProxy.toJs` method is when the buffer is bitmapped image data. If for "
"instance you have a 3d buffer shaped 1920 x 1080 x 4, then {js:func}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` will be extremely slow. In this case you could "
"use {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyBuffer.getBuffer`. On the other hand, if you "
"have a 3d buffer shaped 1920 x 4 x 1080, the performance of {js:func}"
"`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.toJs` will most likely be satisfactory. Typically, the "
"innermost dimension won't matter for performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:647
msgid ""
"The {js:func}`~pyodide.ffi.PyBuffer.getBuffer` method can be used to "
"retrieve a reference to a JavaScript typed array that points to the data "
"backing the Python object, combined with other metadata about the buffer "
"format. The metadata is suitable for use with a JavaScript ndarray library "
"if one is present. For instance, if you load the JavaScript [ndarray]"
"(https://github.com/scijs/ndarray) package, you can do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:654
msgid ""
"const proxy = pyodide.globals.get(\"some_numpy_ndarray\");\n"
"const buffer = proxy.getBuffer();\n"
"proxy.destroy();\n"
"try {\n"
"  if (buffer.readonly) {\n"
"    // We can't stop you from changing a readonly buffer, but it can cause\n"
"    // undefined behavior.\n"
"    throw new Error(\"Uh-oh, we were planning to change the buffer\");\n"
"  }\n"
"  const array = new ndarray(\n"
"    buffer.data,\n"
"    buffer.shape,\n"
"    buffer.strides,\n"
"    buffer.offset,\n"
"  );\n"
"  // manipulate array here\n"
"  // changes will be reflected in the Python ndarray!\n"
"} finally {\n"
"  buffer.release(); // Release the memory when we're done\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:677
msgid ""
"It's also possible to declare the buffer with the `using` keyword and "
"JavaScript resource management:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:680
msgid ""
"{\n"
"    using proxy = pyodide.globals.get(\"some_numpy_ndarray\");\n"
"    using buffer = proxy.getBuffer();\n"
"    const array = new ndarray(\n"
"        buffer.data,\n"
"        buffer.shape,\n"
"        buffer.strides,\n"
"        buffer.offset,\n"
"    );\n"
"    // manipulate array here\n"
"}\n"
"// proxy destroyed and buffer released automatically at end of scope!\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:697
msgid "Errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:699
msgid ""
"All entrypoints and exit points from Python code are wrapped in JavaScript "
"`try` blocks. At the boundary between Python and JavaScript, errors are "
"caught,s converted between languages, and rethrown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:703
msgid ""
"JavaScript errors are wrapped in a {py:class}`~pyodide.ffi.JsException`. "
"Python exceptions are converted to a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PythonError`. "
"At present if an exception crosses between Python and JavaScript several "
"times, the resulting error message won't be as useful as one might hope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:708
msgid ""
"In order to reduce memory leaks, the {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PythonError` "
"has a formatted traceback, but no reference to the original Python "
"exception. The original exception has references to the stack frame and "
"leaking it will leak all the local variables from that stack frame. The "
"actual Python exception will be stored in {py:data}`sys.last_value` so if "
"you need access to it (for instance to produce a traceback with certain "
"functions filtered out), use that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:715
msgid "Be careful Proxying Stack Frames"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:717
msgid ""
"If you make a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` of {py:data}`sys.last_value`, "
"you should be especially careful to {js:meth}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy.destroy` "
"it when you are done with it, or you may leak a large amount of memory if "
"you don't."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:722
msgid "The easiest way is to only handle the exception in Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:724
msgid ""
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"def reformat_exception():\n"
"    from traceback import format_exception\n"
"    # Format a modified exception here\n"
"    # this just prints it normally but you could for instance filter some "
"frames\n"
"    return \"\".join(\n"
"        format_exception(sys.last_type, sys.last_value, sys.last_traceback)\n"
"    )\n"
"`);\n"
"let reformat_exception = pyodide.globals.get(\"reformat_exception\");\n"
"try {\n"
"    pyodide.runPython(some_code);\n"
"} catch(e){\n"
"    // replace error message\n"
"    e.message = reformat_exception();\n"
"    throw e;\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:744
msgid "Importing Objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:746
msgid ""
"It is possible to access objects in one language from the global scope in "
"the other language. It is also possible to create custom namespaces and "
"access objects on the custom namespaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:752
msgid "Importing Python objects into JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:754
msgid ""
"A Python global variable in the `__main__` global scope can be imported into "
"JavaScript using the {js:meth}`pyodide.globals.get() <pyodide.ffi."
"PyProxyWithGet.get>` method. Given the name of the Python global variable, "
"it returns the value of the variable translated to JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:759
msgid "let x = pyodide.globals.get(\"x\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:763
msgid ""
"As always, if the result is a {js:class}`~pyodide.ffi.PyProxy` and you care "
"about not leaking the Python object, you must destroy it when you are done. "
"It's also possible to set values in the Python global scope with {js:meth}"
"`pyodide.globals.set() <pyodide.ffi.PyProxyWithSet.set>` or remove them with "
"{js:meth}`pyodide.globals.delete() <pyodide.ffi.PyProxyWithSet.delete>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:769
msgid ""
"pyodide.globals.set(\"x\", 2);\n"
"pyodide.runPython(\"print(x)\"); // Prints 2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:774
msgid ""
"If you execute code with a custom globals dictionary, you can use a similar "
"approach:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:777
msgid ""
"let my_py_namespace = pyodide.globals.get(\"dict\")();\n"
"pyodide.runPython(\"x=2\", my_py_namespace);\n"
"let x = my_py_namespace.get(\"x\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:783
msgid ""
"To access a Python module from JavaScript, use {js:func}`~pyodide.pyimport`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:785
msgid "let sys = pyodide.pyimport(\"sys\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:791
msgid "Importing JavaScript objects into Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:793
msgid ""
"JavaScript objects in the {js:data}`globalThis` global scope can be imported "
"into Python using the `js` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:796
msgid ""
"When importing a name from the `js` module, the `js` module looks up "
"JavaScript attributes of the {js:data}`globalThis` scope and translates the "
"JavaScript objects into Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:800
msgid ""
"import js\n"
"js.document.title = 'New window title'\n"
"from js.document.location import reload as reload_page\n"
"reload_page()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:807
msgid "You can also assign to JavaScript global variables in this way:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:809
msgid ""
"pyodide.runPython(\"js.x = 2\");\n"
"console.log(window.x); // 2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:814
msgid ""
"You can create your own custom JavaScript modules using {js:func}`pyodide."
"registerJsModule` and they will behave like the `js` module except with a "
"custom scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:818
msgid ""
"let my_js_namespace = { x : 3 };\n"
"pyodide.registerJsModule(\"my_js_namespace\", my_js_namespace);\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from my_js_namespace import x\n"
"    print(x) # 3\n"
"    my_js_namespace.y = 7\n"
"`);\n"
"console.log(my_js_namespace.y); // 7\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:829
msgid ""
"If the JavaScript object's name is a reserved Python keyword, the {py:func}"
"`getattr` function can be used to access the object by name within the js "
"module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:833
msgid ""
"lambda = (x) => {return x + 1};\n"
"// 'from js import lambda' will cause a Syntax Error, since 'lambda' is a "
"Python reserved keyword. Instead:\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    import js\n"
"    js_lambda = getattr(js, 'lambda')\n"
"    print(js_lambda(1))\n"
"    `);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:843
msgid ""
"If a JavaScript object has a property that is a reserved Python keyword, the "
"{py:func}`setattr` and {py:func}`getattr` function can be used to access "
"that property by name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../usage/type-conversions.md:847
msgid ""
"people = {global: \"lots and lots\"};\n"
"// Trying to access 'people.global' will raise a Syntax Error, since\n"
"// 'global' is a Python reserved keyword. Instead:\n"
"pyodide.runPython(`\n"
"    from js import people\n"
"    people.global_ = 'even more'\n"
"    print(people.global_)\n"
"`);\n"
msgstr ""
